name: Chris Paul Towers
tweet: There are exceptions to the ‚ÄúADP is is a rational marketplace‚Äù idea, of course ‚Äî what are we doing with Pete Alonso, guys ‚Äî but the truth of the matter is it‚Äôs harder than ever to find an edge in Fantasy baseball. Which means you have to take bold chances.

name: Chris Paul Towers
tweet: But, one of the things about Fantasy Baseball in 2020 is, everyone is sharp. You don‚Äôt find an edge by identifying the likeliest outcome for every player and drafting accordingly, because you‚Äôll mostly end up following ADP. The market has become very efficient.

name: Chris Paul Towers
tweet: And this is what makes small sample sizes so frustrating. Even a full season isn‚Äôt enough of a sample to say with confidence what a player‚Äôs true skill level is, and so breakouts in ever small samples just make it harder and harder to have confidence.

name: Chris Paul Towers
tweet: June 1 on, Buehler had a 122 IP stretch with a 2.88 ERA, 1.016 WHIP, and 31.78% strikeout rate.  That‚Äôs basically what Clevinger did in his 2019, more or less. But Buehler had the April and May, while we only saw that stretch from Clevinger. Would he have regressed? Who knows!

name: Chris Paul Towers
tweet: The case for Clevinger is, I think, that his 2019 is better than anything we‚Äôve seen from either of them.  However, there‚Äôs *probably* a comparable 126-inning stretch in Buehler‚Äôs game log somewhere, which is why Clevinger only throwing 126 IP is so frustrating.
